WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.415 --> 00:00:02.998
(bright music)

2
00:00:07.980 --> 00:00:09.840
<v David>Dr. Levine is an associate professor</v>

3
00:00:09.840 --> 00:00:11.190
in the Department of Family Medicine

4
00:00:11.190 --> 00:00:14.310
at the Brody School of Medicine at East Carolina University.

5
00:00:14.310 --> 00:00:17.460
He is well acquainted with preparing individuals

6
00:00:17.460 --> 00:00:20.789
for board examinations, expert educator,

7
00:00:20.789 --> 00:00:22.470
and we're delighted to have him here.

8
00:00:22.470 --> 00:00:23.970
So, Gary, take it away.

9
00:00:23.970 --> 00:00:26.340
Good morning, sir, I appreciate you're being here.

10
00:00:26.340 --> 00:00:28.440
<v ->Well, thank you for that kind introduction, David,</v>

11
00:00:28.440 --> 00:00:30.780
and welcome, everybody.

12
00:00:30.780 --> 00:00:32.670
I don't have any disclaimers.

13
00:00:32.670 --> 00:00:36.041
I don't have any investments or anything

14
00:00:36.041 --> 00:00:39.220
or relationships with companies that would create bias

15
00:00:39.220 --> 00:00:42.813
in the information that we bring to you today.

16
00:00:44.340 --> 00:00:46.410
Now, the kidney is a very important part

17
00:00:46.410 --> 00:00:47.820
of our body as you know.

18
00:00:47.820 --> 00:00:52.020
Helps us to maintain our fluid environment,

19
00:00:52.020 --> 00:00:54.960
to excrete waste products, maintain water,

20
00:00:54.960 --> 00:00:58.500
electrolyte, and acid-based balance.

21
00:00:58.500 --> 00:01:00.630
It also secretes hormones,

22
00:01:00.630 --> 00:01:02.880
the renin, angiotensin system

23
00:01:02.880 --> 00:01:05.190
that works with our hemodynamics,

24
00:01:05.190 --> 00:01:07.530
erythropoietin to make red cells,

25
00:01:07.530 --> 00:01:10.923
and vitamin D analogs for our bone metabolism.

26
00:01:11.850 --> 00:01:13.560
When you see patients in the office,

27
00:01:13.560 --> 00:01:16.440
often you do a urinalysis, a dipstick,

28
00:01:16.440 --> 00:01:18.390
your nurse does that for you,

29
00:01:18.390 --> 00:01:20.280
and you're looking there pretty much

30
00:01:20.280 --> 00:01:23.820
for the presence of blood or protein or pus

31
00:01:23.820 --> 00:01:25.350
essentially in there.

32
00:01:25.350 --> 00:01:27.900
And we tell our residents, "Well, don't stop there."

33
00:01:27.900 --> 00:01:29.498
If there are any abnormalities,

34
00:01:29.498 --> 00:01:33.420
do a microscopic urine because it's very, very helpful,

35
00:01:33.420 --> 00:01:35.700
and I hope you all do that still.

36
00:01:35.700 --> 00:01:37.470
The board loves to ask you a question

37
00:01:37.470 --> 00:01:40.440
where there is a dipstick positive for blood,

38
00:01:40.440 --> 00:01:44.400
but there are no RBCs on that microscopic exam.

39
00:01:44.400 --> 00:01:47.040
So think in that case about hemolysis,

40
00:01:47.040 --> 00:01:49.225
think about rhabdomyolysis.

41
00:01:49.225 --> 00:01:51.090
They also may try to trick you

42
00:01:51.090 --> 00:01:54.390
and say that the urine dipstick is positive for protein,

43
00:01:54.390 --> 00:01:56.730
so the patient must have myeloma.

44
00:01:56.730 --> 00:01:59.340
Well, the positive protein is only albumin,

45
00:01:59.340 --> 00:02:01.860
and you're not gonna detect Bence Jones protein

46
00:02:01.860 --> 00:02:03.720
on a dipstick alone.

47
00:02:03.720 --> 00:02:07.650
If you see white cells and probably UTI,

48
00:02:07.650 --> 00:02:08.850
but if you see white cells

49
00:02:08.850 --> 00:02:10.830
and there are no bacteria in there,

50
00:02:10.830 --> 00:02:14.250
think about chlamydia, gonorrhea, think about prostatitis.

51
00:02:14.250 --> 00:02:16.680
And if it look like eosinophils,

52
00:02:16.680 --> 00:02:19.080
the board loves interstitial nephritis,

53
00:02:19.080 --> 00:02:21.390
so think about that one as well.

54
00:02:21.390 --> 00:02:24.210
Hyaline, granular cast can be normal,

55
00:02:24.210 --> 00:02:27.330
but muddy brown cast, think about ATN

56
00:02:27.330 --> 00:02:29.250
in the appropriate setting.

57
00:02:29.250 --> 00:02:32.520
If there are red cell casts, glomerulonephritis.

58
00:02:32.520 --> 00:02:35.430
If there are white cell casts, pyelonephritis.

59
00:02:35.430 --> 00:02:37.290
So that microscopic exam

60
00:02:37.290 --> 00:02:39.421
gives you a lot of good information.

61
00:02:39.421 --> 00:02:43.620
We also are important in our appreciation

62
00:02:43.620 --> 00:02:45.110
of renal function

63
00:02:45.110 --> 00:02:48.586
and a way to measure that certainly is the GFR,

64
00:02:48.586 --> 00:02:51.270
which is kind of the holy grail of things.

65
00:02:51.270 --> 00:02:53.280
They do it in a research lab.

66
00:02:53.280 --> 00:02:55.530
We can measure creatinine clearance,

67
00:02:55.530 --> 00:02:57.810
but typically don't measure it.

68
00:02:57.810 --> 00:02:59.540
We do measure creatinine

69
00:02:59.540 --> 00:03:03.450
in their various formulas we use to estimate GFR

70
00:03:03.450 --> 00:03:06.030
or estimate creatinine clearance.

71
00:03:06.030 --> 00:03:09.989
The MDRD formula has been around for a long time.

72
00:03:09.989 --> 00:03:14.430
As you notice, it has a correction for age, sex,

73
00:03:14.430 --> 00:03:16.297
used to have a correction for race,

74
00:03:16.297 --> 00:03:18.570
and does not have a correction for weight.

75
00:03:18.570 --> 00:03:23.190
So it may underestimate the GFR in large people

76
00:03:23.190 --> 00:03:26.160
and overestimate it in smaller people.

77
00:03:26.160 --> 00:03:28.968
There's also something called the CKD-EPI.

78
00:03:28.968 --> 00:03:31.080
We don't do that.

79
00:03:31.080 --> 00:03:33.390
Most of the nephrologists do however

80
00:03:33.390 --> 00:03:36.450
because they use of something called cystatin C

81
00:03:36.450 --> 00:03:38.610
instead of creatinine in the equation.

82
00:03:38.610 --> 00:03:42.720
More expensive, not as well available for us.

83
00:03:42.720 --> 00:03:46.121
The Cockcroft-Gault equation's been around for a long time.

84
00:03:46.121 --> 00:03:49.391
This has a, again, a modification for age

85
00:03:49.391 --> 00:03:53.190
and for sex and for weight,

86
00:03:53.190 --> 00:03:55.410
and it's less accurate for renal function

87
00:03:55.410 --> 00:03:57.750
but better for renally-dosing medicines,

88
00:03:57.750 --> 00:03:59.730
especially in the elderly.

89
00:03:59.730 --> 00:04:02.940
The board is not gonna ask you to calculate any of these,

90
00:04:02.940 --> 00:04:07.140
but you may want to know which one is available

91
00:04:07.140 --> 00:04:09.683
for estimating renal function.

92
00:04:09.683 --> 00:04:13.590
In general, if you have a 70-kilogram man

93
00:04:13.590 --> 00:04:15.450
with a creatinine of one,

94
00:04:15.450 --> 00:04:19.080
then the creatinine clearance is roughly 140 minus

95
00:04:19.080 --> 00:04:20.460
that person's age.

96
00:04:20.460 --> 00:04:22.237
And every time you double creatinine,

97
00:04:22.237 --> 00:04:27.237
you decrease GFR or creatinine clearance by about 50%.

98
00:04:28.950 --> 00:04:31.320
If you want more information on these calculators

99
00:04:31.320 --> 00:04:34.920
and equations or anything at all about renal function,

100
00:04:34.920 --> 00:04:38.550
you can go to this website from the Kidney Organization.

101
00:04:38.550 --> 00:04:40.740
I guarantee you that after half an hour,

102
00:04:40.740 --> 00:04:42.030
you'd be ready for bed.

103
00:04:42.030 --> 00:04:43.180
It'll put you to sleep.

104
00:04:44.040 --> 00:04:46.827
Protein excretion also very important.

105
00:04:46.827 --> 00:04:49.050
We used to have 24-hour collections.

106
00:04:49.050 --> 00:04:51.155
Patient will carry these jugs around with them.

107
00:04:51.155 --> 00:04:53.130
Don't do that anymore.

108
00:04:53.130 --> 00:04:55.530
We use spot collections now.

109
00:04:55.530 --> 00:04:57.660
A normal protein excretion

110
00:04:57.660 --> 00:05:01.382
would be less than 150 milligrams per 24 hours.

111
00:05:01.382 --> 00:05:03.000
Over three grams,

112
00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:06.810
what we call nephrotic range proteinuria.

113
00:05:06.810 --> 00:05:08.310
We also often measure

114
00:05:08.310 --> 00:05:11.520
the urine microalbumin creatinine ratio.

115
00:05:11.520 --> 00:05:13.980
A ratio of less than 30 is normal,

116
00:05:13.980 --> 00:05:17.340
30 to 300 is microalbuminuria,

117
00:05:17.340 --> 00:05:20.340
over 300 macroalbuminuria.

118
00:05:20.340 --> 00:05:22.243
We're gonna see this time and time again

119
00:05:22.243 --> 00:05:25.443
as we talk about diabetic kidney disease.

120
00:05:26.312 --> 00:05:29.460
Moving on, I'll talk a little bit about AKI,

121
00:05:29.460 --> 00:05:30.540
acute kidney injury.

122
00:05:30.540 --> 00:05:33.333
We used to call this acute renal failure.

123
00:05:34.410 --> 00:05:37.833
Early recognition of this may help prevent it from worsening

124
00:05:37.833 --> 00:05:40.713
and causing multiorgan system failure.

125
00:05:41.910 --> 00:05:43.950
If people get AKI and die,

126
00:05:43.950 --> 00:05:45.963
it's not typically from uremia,

127
00:05:45.963 --> 00:05:48.090
it's typically from infections

128
00:05:48.090 --> 00:05:50.370
and cardiopulmonary complications.

129
00:05:50.370 --> 00:05:51.390
We'll see the same thing

130
00:05:51.390 --> 00:05:53.823
with chronic kidney disease as well.

131
00:05:55.020 --> 00:05:56.760
How do you diagnose AKI?

132
00:05:56.760 --> 00:06:00.090
It's an objective diagnosis, not symptomatic,

133
00:06:00.090 --> 00:06:02.640
it's based on changes in creatinine

134
00:06:02.640 --> 00:06:05.370
and changes in urine output.

135
00:06:05.370 --> 00:06:10.370
KDIGO, which is an organization in the nephrology world,

136
00:06:10.566 --> 00:06:15.450
brought us a minimal criteria for AKI diagnosis.

137
00:06:15.450 --> 00:06:19.380
They include an absolute increase in creatinine

138
00:06:19.380 --> 00:06:23.809
of 0.3 milligrams per deciliter within two days

139
00:06:23.809 --> 00:06:28.809
or an increase to 1.5 times baseline within seven days.

140
00:06:30.270 --> 00:06:34.866
Or urine volume of less than 0.5 ml per kilogram per hour

141
00:06:34.866 --> 00:06:37.140
lasting more than six hours.

142
00:06:37.140 --> 00:06:39.810
Any of those will qualify your patient

143
00:06:39.810 --> 00:06:41.347
for a diagnosis of AKI.

144
00:06:42.274 --> 00:06:46.380
AKI can be oliguric or can be anuric

145
00:06:46.380 --> 00:06:48.663
or can occur with normal urine output.

146
00:06:50.250 --> 00:06:52.203
Let's look at a question for you.

147
00:06:53.520 --> 00:06:55.680
See how you do.

148
00:06:55.680 --> 00:06:57.280
The most common cause of AKI

149
00:06:58.830 --> 00:07:00.213
is which of the following?

150
00:07:01.200 --> 00:07:04.200
Ureteral calculus with hydronephrosis,

151
00:07:04.200 --> 00:07:06.660
diuretic-induced volume depletion,

152
00:07:06.660 --> 00:07:08.610
acute tubular necrosis,

153
00:07:08.610 --> 00:07:10.623
or acute interstitial nephritis.

154
00:07:12.360 --> 00:07:14.190
If you work in the hospital setting,

155
00:07:14.190 --> 00:07:16.923
this is something that's pretty obvious for you.

156
00:07:21.568 --> 00:07:26.400
And you have voted for B, and B is not right.

157
00:07:26.400 --> 00:07:29.280
It's actually ATN but don't feel bad

158
00:07:29.280 --> 00:07:30.270
'cause none of the groups

159
00:07:30.270 --> 00:07:32.640
have generally got this one correct.

160
00:07:32.640 --> 00:07:37.016
So ATN counts for about 45% of AKI

161
00:07:37.016 --> 00:07:40.788
were prerenal disease including that diuresis

162
00:07:40.788 --> 00:07:43.200
and nausea, vomiting, diarrhea.

163
00:07:43.200 --> 00:07:45.900
It's only about 21%.

164
00:07:45.900 --> 00:07:50.900
UTIs weigh down the list, obstruction only about 10%.

165
00:07:50.970 --> 00:07:54.450
Glomerulonephritis weigh down the list as well.

166
00:07:54.450 --> 00:07:59.450
So ATN and number two would be prerenal causes.

167
00:07:59.640 --> 00:08:03.690
Prerenal causes can be either actual volume depletion

168
00:08:03.690 --> 00:08:05.730
or disease entities that decrease

169
00:08:05.730 --> 00:08:08.430
effective arterial blood volume.

170
00:08:08.430 --> 00:08:10.857
Some medicines can also do that

171
00:08:10.857 --> 00:08:12.903
and cause prerenal AKI.

172
00:08:13.920 --> 00:08:15.780
Volume depletion can be bleeding,

173
00:08:15.780 --> 00:08:19.443
can be nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, can be burns,

174
00:08:21.690 --> 00:08:26.430
shock, heart failure, cirrhosis, PE,

175
00:08:26.430 --> 00:08:29.193
can also cause decreased renal perfusion.

176
00:08:30.660 --> 00:08:33.930
Intrarenal causes are very common.

177
00:08:33.930 --> 00:08:36.840
ATN being a tubular cause.

178
00:08:36.840 --> 00:08:38.730
They're also interstitial reasons.

179
00:08:38.730 --> 00:08:42.480
Glomerular and vascular causes of AKI.

180
00:08:42.480 --> 00:08:45.480
We mentioned ATN being the most common.

181
00:08:45.480 --> 00:08:48.270
You see this with patients who have hypotension,

182
00:08:48.270 --> 00:08:52.380
even a short period of that can cause ATN.

183
00:08:52.380 --> 00:08:57.380
Ischemia, burns, post-op patients, or rhabdo, all can do it.

184
00:08:57.810 --> 00:09:00.474
There's no specific ATN treatment.

185
00:09:00.474 --> 00:09:02.910
You wanna treat the underlying disease process

186
00:09:02.910 --> 00:09:04.773
and avoid hypotension.

187
00:09:05.774 --> 00:09:08.970
Acute interstitial nephritis, AIN,

188
00:09:08.970 --> 00:09:10.903
board happens to like this one.

189
00:09:10.903 --> 00:09:15.473
This is typically caused by drugs or autoimmune disorders.

190
00:09:15.473 --> 00:09:18.059
Symptoms include fevers, rashes,

191
00:09:18.059 --> 00:09:21.750
and the presence of eosinophils in the urine,

192
00:09:21.750 --> 00:09:23.430
so look for that.

193
00:09:23.430 --> 00:09:26.010
If you find this, stop the offending drug,

194
00:09:26.010 --> 00:09:28.170
treat the underlying infection,

195
00:09:28.170 --> 00:09:30.783
treat the autoimmune problem, and they get better.

196
00:09:32.674 --> 00:09:35.370
Question number two for you.

197
00:09:35.370 --> 00:09:38.660
Speaking of AIN, which of the following drugs

198
00:09:38.660 --> 00:09:41.490
is the most commonly associated with it?

199
00:09:41.490 --> 00:09:45.993
Pregabalin or ertapenem, omeprazole, or fluoxetine.

200
00:09:52.350 --> 00:09:54.060
And you have voted for omeprazole.

201
00:09:54.060 --> 00:09:56.940
Excellent, that is in fact true.

202
00:09:56.940 --> 00:09:59.850
There are a number of drugs associated with AIN,

203
00:09:59.850 --> 00:10:02.460
many of which are commonly used antibiotics,

204
00:10:02.460 --> 00:10:04.110
have been around forever.

205
00:10:04.110 --> 00:10:07.581
Phenytoin can as well, NSAIDs can,

206
00:10:07.581 --> 00:10:11.340
but the newer agents on the block, so to speak,

207
00:10:11.340 --> 00:10:15.210
are the PPIs, probably a class effect of all of them,

208
00:10:15.210 --> 00:10:17.100
not dose related.

209
00:10:17.100 --> 00:10:22.100
Not only does it increase AIN at a four or five times ratio,

210
00:10:22.200 --> 00:10:24.760
it can also cause CKD

211
00:10:24.760 --> 00:10:27.663
in patients with underlying renal disease.

212
00:10:28.743 --> 00:10:32.010
There are multiple other entities cause AKI.

213
00:10:32.010 --> 00:10:35.100
Other tubular interstitial diseases include myeloma,

214
00:10:35.100 --> 00:10:38.220
hypercalcemia, the tumor lysis syndrome

215
00:10:38.220 --> 00:10:40.410
in patients treated with chemotherapy

216
00:10:40.410 --> 00:10:43.680
and phosphate nephropathy.

217
00:10:43.680 --> 00:10:45.600
We used to use sodium phosphate

218
00:10:45.600 --> 00:10:47.940
as a clean out for colonoscopy.

219
00:10:47.940 --> 00:10:51.633
We stopped it when we found it caused AKI in patients.

220
00:10:52.980 --> 00:10:56.610
There are glomerular causes as well of AKI.

221
00:10:56.610 --> 00:10:57.990
They're uncommon.

222
00:10:57.990 --> 00:11:00.780
Think of these when you have systemic side effects

223
00:11:00.780 --> 00:11:03.793
and manifestations, fever, rash, arthralgias,

224
00:11:03.793 --> 00:11:06.565
when there's an abnormal urine sediment,

225
00:11:06.565 --> 00:11:08.730
these patients may need to be seen

226
00:11:08.730 --> 00:11:12.330
by the nephrologist and even biopsy.

227
00:11:12.330 --> 00:11:14.670
There are two types of glomerular diseases.

228
00:11:14.670 --> 00:11:17.220
Nephritic and nephrotic.

229
00:11:17.220 --> 00:11:21.060
Nephritic, those patients have red cell casts in the urine.

230
00:11:21.060 --> 00:11:22.200
They're hypertensive.

231
00:11:22.200 --> 00:11:24.480
They may have mild proteinuria.

232
00:11:24.480 --> 00:11:28.170
Whereas your nephrotic are bloated, edematous folks,

233
00:11:28.170 --> 00:11:29.724
massive proteinuria.

234
00:11:29.724 --> 00:11:32.670
They may have hypercoagulable states

235
00:11:32.670 --> 00:11:34.503
and their lipids are off the wall.

236
00:11:35.520 --> 00:11:39.354
The board is not likely gonna ask you specific entities

237
00:11:39.354 --> 00:11:41.190
in these categories.

238
00:11:41.190 --> 00:11:45.240
But if they may give you a urine sediment

239
00:11:45.240 --> 00:11:49.080
that looks nephrItic or a obvious proteinuric state

240
00:11:49.080 --> 00:11:52.500
with bloating, you may wanna identify that as nephrotic.

241
00:11:52.500 --> 00:11:53.910
But some nephritic diseases

242
00:11:53.910 --> 00:11:56.847
include postinfectious glomerulonephritis,

243
00:11:56.847 --> 00:12:01.170
IgA nephropathy, membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis,

244
00:12:01.170 --> 00:12:03.240
HS purpura.

245
00:12:03.240 --> 00:12:05.610
Your nephrotic are your diabetics,

246
00:12:05.610 --> 00:12:07.440
minimal change disease,

247
00:12:07.440 --> 00:12:11.040
your membranous glomerulonephritis, amyloidosis.

248
00:12:11.040 --> 00:12:12.873
Those are nephrotic diseases.

249
00:12:14.070 --> 00:12:18.270
Vascular cause of AKI include vasculitis like Wegener's.

250
00:12:18.270 --> 00:12:21.780
There was a question of Wegener's many years ago.

251
00:12:21.780 --> 00:12:24.360
Thromboembolic disease, malignant hypertension,

252
00:12:24.360 --> 00:12:26.403
scleroderma, for example.

253
00:12:27.390 --> 00:12:30.183
Postrenal causes not a common cause of AKI.

254
00:12:31.140 --> 00:12:33.330
The good news is that's the reason

255
00:12:33.330 --> 00:12:35.370
then it's pretty reversible

256
00:12:35.370 --> 00:12:38.880
and ultrasounds are a good way to assess for that

257
00:12:38.880 --> 00:12:41.133
in any patient who has AKI.

258
00:12:42.150 --> 00:12:45.780
Some of these causes include urethral valves in children,

259
00:12:45.780 --> 00:12:49.530
urethral strictures, renal calculi, BPH,

260
00:12:49.530 --> 00:12:53.013
and prostate cancer or pelvic neoplasms.

261
00:12:54.150 --> 00:12:58.200
Who needs a biopsy in the face of AKI?

262
00:12:58.200 --> 00:13:01.020
People who are getting worse, they're oliguric.

263
00:13:01.020 --> 00:13:06.020
You excluded other causes of prerenal or postrenal causes.

264
00:13:06.053 --> 00:13:09.091
You're thinking of putting them on immunosuppressants.

265
00:13:09.091 --> 00:13:11.760
Then you and the nephrologist may wanna move

266
00:13:11.760 --> 00:13:13.023
in that direction.

267
00:13:14.961 --> 00:13:17.853
Question number three, we're doing good so far.

268
00:13:18.840 --> 00:13:22.500
70-year-old man scheduled to have a CT of his abdomen

269
00:13:22.500 --> 00:13:25.740
with IV contrast to look for a tumor.

270
00:13:25.740 --> 00:13:28.203
He has Type II diabetes, creatinine is 2.8,

271
00:13:29.640 --> 00:13:32.239
which one of the following will most likely decrease

272
00:13:32.239 --> 00:13:36.003
the possibility of contrast-related nephropathy?

273
00:13:37.380 --> 00:13:40.050
Hydration with isotonic solutions,

274
00:13:40.050 --> 00:13:43.650
oral acetylcysteine twice a day for 48 hours,

275
00:13:43.650 --> 00:13:46.980
beginning the day following the procedure,

276
00:13:46.980 --> 00:13:49.770
acidification of the urine with ascorbic acid,

277
00:13:49.770 --> 00:13:52.860
vitamin C beginning 24 hours before

278
00:13:52.860 --> 00:13:55.860
and continuing for 48 hours afterwards

279
00:13:55.860 --> 00:13:57.870
or asking the radiologist to use

280
00:13:57.870 --> 00:14:00.693
a hyperosmolar contrast medium.

281
00:14:06.540 --> 00:14:10.620
Hydration with isotonic solution is the answer.

282
00:14:10.620 --> 00:14:14.490
This brings us to the topic of contrast-induced nephropathy,

283
00:14:14.490 --> 00:14:16.980
kind of a controversial topic.

284
00:14:16.980 --> 00:14:20.871
It has different names now including post-contrast AKI

285
00:14:20.871 --> 00:14:23.744
or contrast associated AKI,

286
00:14:23.744 --> 00:14:25.860
usually happens in 48 hours

287
00:14:25.860 --> 00:14:27.783
when you administer these agents.

288
00:14:28.860 --> 00:14:31.410
The decline in renal function typically begins

289
00:14:31.410 --> 00:14:34.530
about 48 hours afterwards like we said.

290
00:14:34.530 --> 00:14:36.750
Follow a predictable course,

291
00:14:36.750 --> 00:14:39.480
typically is better within a week.

292
00:14:39.480 --> 00:14:44.210
Usually reversible, but we believe to be preventable.

293
00:14:44.210 --> 00:14:46.426
It is controversial where the risk

294
00:14:46.426 --> 00:14:48.630
that we were really worried about in the past

295
00:14:48.630 --> 00:14:50.910
is probably overstated.

296
00:14:50.910 --> 00:14:52.440
But the lower the GFR,

297
00:14:52.440 --> 00:14:54.360
probably the greater the risk

298
00:14:54.360 --> 00:14:56.880
that this will happen to your patient.

299
00:14:56.880 --> 00:14:59.302
So patients with a GFR of less than 60,

300
00:14:59.302 --> 00:15:01.878
maybe a 5% risk at best,

301
00:15:01.878 --> 00:15:05.883
less than 30, maybe a 30% risk at best.

302
00:15:07.290 --> 00:15:11.790
Post-contrast AKI to avoid this,

303
00:15:11.790 --> 00:15:14.078
try to avoid using that medium

304
00:15:14.078 --> 00:15:17.040
in patients really at risk for AKI.

305
00:15:17.040 --> 00:15:17.873
Those are those.

306
00:15:17.873 --> 00:15:19.620
We have CKD to begin with,

307
00:15:19.620 --> 00:15:23.160
are dehydrated, diabetic, sickle cell disease

308
00:15:23.160 --> 00:15:25.203
or the very elderly.

309
00:15:26.220 --> 00:15:29.400
There's a lot of literature coming out of emergency medicine

310
00:15:29.400 --> 00:15:33.300
primarily that says this is not all that important,

311
00:15:33.300 --> 00:15:36.602
came out in the 2017, 2018 range,

312
00:15:36.602 --> 00:15:38.910
and it's pretty good data.

313
00:15:38.910 --> 00:15:42.690
But the ED docs and the kidney docs got together,

314
00:15:42.690 --> 00:15:45.157
and they have a consensus statement that says,

315
00:15:45.157 --> 00:15:47.370
"One, the risk is overstated,

316
00:15:47.370 --> 00:15:49.170
but it may be there.

317
00:15:49.170 --> 00:15:51.240
Uncertain patients with kidney disease

318
00:15:51.240 --> 00:15:53.100
even when it's severe,

319
00:15:53.100 --> 00:15:56.940
but you can prevent it by IV saline infusion

320
00:15:56.940 --> 00:15:58.800
in appropriate patients,

321
00:15:58.800 --> 00:16:03.800
particularly those with AKI, low GFRs, or at high risk."

322
00:16:05.310 --> 00:16:06.960
So there you have it.

323
00:16:06.960 --> 00:16:08.910
Other things you wanna do may wanna do

324
00:16:08.910 --> 00:16:13.910
before a dye study is hold metformin for about 48 hours,

325
00:16:14.100 --> 00:16:16.830
hold their diuretics at high risk patients,

326
00:16:16.830 --> 00:16:18.690
again, hydrate them.

327
00:16:18.690 --> 00:16:21.290
There's no good data to support alkalization

328
00:16:21.290 --> 00:16:23.403
or acetylcysteine anymore.

329
00:16:25.140 --> 00:16:28.290
There are a lot of drugs that cause nephrotoxicity,

330
00:16:28.290 --> 00:16:30.480
but there are a few that you really might wanna know about,

331
00:16:30.480 --> 00:16:31.353
pre-boards.

332
00:16:32.250 --> 00:16:35.580
NSAIDs, you know, our nephrologists wear badges like this

333
00:16:35.580 --> 00:16:40.580
with a no NSAID kind of diagonal red line,

334
00:16:41.010 --> 00:16:43.470
lithium, certain antibiotics,

335
00:16:43.470 --> 00:16:45.960
especially combinations of aminoglycosides

336
00:16:45.960 --> 00:16:49.004
and vancomycin, amphoterrible,

337
00:16:49.004 --> 00:16:51.843
IV acyclovir can do that as well.

338
00:16:52.740 --> 00:16:54.451
What about ACEs and ARBs?

339
00:16:54.451 --> 00:16:55.890
They're not nephrotoxic,

340
00:16:55.890 --> 00:16:58.830
but in the setting of AKI, you may want to hold them

341
00:16:58.830 --> 00:17:00.990
until the renal function improves.

342
00:17:00.990 --> 00:17:03.660
Same thing with diuretics, PPIs,

343
00:17:03.660 --> 00:17:05.970
and watch out for methotrexate.

344
00:17:05.970 --> 00:17:07.710
What about metformin?

345
00:17:07.710 --> 00:17:11.130
Metformin can increase the risk of lactic acidosis.

346
00:17:11.130 --> 00:17:14.490
So the guidelines have been around now for almost 10 years,

347
00:17:14.490 --> 00:17:19.290
say don't start metformin for GFR less than 45.

348
00:17:19.290 --> 00:17:21.480
If a patient on it and hits 45,

349
00:17:21.480 --> 00:17:25.080
consider decreasing your dose by 50%

350
00:17:25.080 --> 00:17:28.293
and don't start it if a GFR is less than 30.

351
00:17:29.420 --> 00:17:32.370
Enoxaparin, use that with caution.

352
00:17:32.370 --> 00:17:36.330
Patients with renal dysfunction, use heparin instead.

353
00:17:36.330 --> 00:17:39.270
Nitrofurantoin needs to be metabolized

354
00:17:39.270 --> 00:17:42.270
excreted in the kidneys in order to work.

355
00:17:42.270 --> 00:17:44.820
We used to say don't use it with GFRs,

356
00:17:44.820 --> 00:17:46.440
anything less than 60.

357
00:17:46.440 --> 00:17:49.860
Now, you can use it with GFRs down to 30,

358
00:17:49.860 --> 00:17:52.713
but you may want to use a shorter course of therapy.

359
00:17:54.180 --> 00:17:55.800
Our next question for you,

360
00:17:55.800 --> 00:17:57.480
you are reviewing the lab findings

361
00:17:57.480 --> 00:17:59.883
of a 64-year-old man hospitalized AKI,

362
00:18:01.110 --> 00:18:04.530
who has no history of any long-term medication use.

363
00:18:04.530 --> 00:18:06.300
Renal function has been normal,

364
00:18:06.300 --> 00:18:09.720
but now the creatinine's 2.8, BUN 60.

365
00:18:09.720 --> 00:18:14.040
To the gravity 1.025, urine sediment hyaline cast.

366
00:18:14.040 --> 00:18:17.183
His FENa, F-E-N-A, is 0.5%.

367
00:18:18.720 --> 00:18:19.950
Based on these findings,

368
00:18:19.950 --> 00:18:23.010
which one the following is most likely?

369
00:18:23.010 --> 00:18:25.539
Is it his hypovolemia from vomiting,

370
00:18:25.539 --> 00:18:29.580
acute pyelonephritis, interstitial nephritis,

371
00:18:29.580 --> 00:18:31.267
or obstruction from BPH?

372
00:18:37.953 --> 00:18:40.020
And you voted for the first one, great.

373
00:18:40.020 --> 00:18:41.850
This is hypovolemia.

374
00:18:41.850 --> 00:18:45.480
And this is the FENa question.

375
00:18:45.480 --> 00:18:48.900
The board is not likely gonna ask you to calculate a FENa,

376
00:18:48.900 --> 00:18:53.040
but it may likely ask you what you're gonna order to do so.

377
00:18:53.040 --> 00:18:56.700
And you're gonna order a urine sodium and urine creatinine

378
00:18:56.700 --> 00:18:59.520
and a plasma sodium, a plasma creatinine,

379
00:18:59.520 --> 00:19:01.650
order to calculate that.

380
00:19:01.650 --> 00:19:03.337
A FENa of less than one is prerenal.

381
00:19:03.337 --> 00:19:08.337
A FENa of over two to three is intrarenal and generally ATN,

382
00:19:09.327 --> 00:19:11.763
and they may ask you that specifically.

383
00:19:14.100 --> 00:19:15.690
Now, using diuretics,

384
00:19:15.690 --> 00:19:18.180
the patient on diuretics can screw up

385
00:19:18.180 --> 00:19:20.190
all the FENa calculations.

386
00:19:20.190 --> 00:19:23.645
The reason for this is that with intrinsic renal disease,

387
00:19:23.645 --> 00:19:27.000
the kidney's a waste sodium.

388
00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:29.880
And that's what you're measuring with a FENa calculation.

389
00:19:29.880 --> 00:19:31.140
So what do diuretics do?

390
00:19:31.140 --> 00:19:34.800
They make you waste sodium to get rid of fluid.

391
00:19:34.800 --> 00:19:38.920
So a patient on diuretics will look like a prerenal...

392
00:19:38.920 --> 00:19:42.000
Look like an intrinsic renal AKI,

393
00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:45.210
rather than a prerenal AKI.

394
00:19:45.210 --> 00:19:48.570
And those patients consider ordering a fractional excretion

395
00:19:48.570 --> 00:19:50.733
of urea instead of a FENa.

396
00:19:52.260 --> 00:19:55.440
To do so, instead of using a serum sodium

397
00:19:55.440 --> 00:19:58.140
and a urine sodium,

398
00:19:58.140 --> 00:20:01.980
you order a BUN and a urine urea,

399
00:20:01.980 --> 00:20:03.830
and then you can do your calculation.

400
00:20:05.355 --> 00:20:07.170
Another limitation of the FENa

401
00:20:07.170 --> 00:20:10.020
is gonna be less than one looking prerenal

402
00:20:10.020 --> 00:20:14.010
if you have ATN superimposed on a chronic renal disease

403
00:20:14.010 --> 00:20:16.290
like heart failure or cirrhosis.

404
00:20:16.290 --> 00:20:19.440
Obstruction can cause FENas to go in any direction,

405
00:20:19.440 --> 00:20:20.793
so it's not helpful there.

406
00:20:22.500 --> 00:20:24.210
Our next question for you.

407
00:20:24.210 --> 00:20:26.880
Metabolic manifestations of AKI include

408
00:20:26.880 --> 00:20:28.350
which of the following?

409
00:20:28.350 --> 00:20:31.550
Metabolic alkalosis, metabolic acidosis,

410
00:20:31.550 --> 00:20:34.893
hypophosphatemia, or hypokalemia.

411
00:20:40.290 --> 00:20:44.310
And 88% of you got this right, it's a metabolic acidosis.

412
00:20:44.310 --> 00:20:47.403
There are many things that happen during AKI,

413
00:20:48.690 --> 00:20:51.300
one are metabolic arrangements.

414
00:20:51.300 --> 00:20:55.060
Usually, the hypers, hyperkalemia, hyperphosphatemia

415
00:20:56.790 --> 00:20:59.670
and acidosis because of the inability

416
00:20:59.670 --> 00:21:02.220
to excrete hydrogen ion.

417
00:21:02.220 --> 00:21:05.700
There are a lot of GI symptoms here.

418
00:21:05.700 --> 00:21:08.040
Nausea, vomiting, diarrhea.

419
00:21:08.040 --> 00:21:11.730
You often will see anemia, neutrophilia,

420
00:21:11.730 --> 00:21:15.510
platelet dysfunction, hypertension,

421
00:21:15.510 --> 00:21:18.870
and neuromuscular disturbances, weakness,

422
00:21:18.870 --> 00:21:22.170
lethargy going onto uremic encephalopathy,

423
00:21:22.170 --> 00:21:25.233
and eventually, you can see coma and death.

424
00:21:26.340 --> 00:21:28.830
How do we manage AKI?

425
00:21:28.830 --> 00:21:31.410
Well, a patient with pretty floored AKI

426
00:21:31.410 --> 00:21:33.450
should be hospitalized.

427
00:21:33.450 --> 00:21:35.160
You may treat them as an outpatient.

428
00:21:35.160 --> 00:21:37.860
If it's mild, you clearly know what's causing it,

429
00:21:37.860 --> 00:21:40.050
and you feel it's reversible.

430
00:21:40.050 --> 00:21:40.890
In the hospitals,

431
00:21:40.890 --> 00:21:44.940
a collaboration between us and the nephrologist

432
00:21:44.940 --> 00:21:46.950
and others who may be involved

433
00:21:46.950 --> 00:21:50.310
and the supportive management treating the primary problem

434
00:21:50.310 --> 00:21:52.170
if you can identify it,

435
00:21:52.170 --> 00:21:55.383
hypertension, sepsis, DKA, et cetera.

436
00:21:56.490 --> 00:21:59.250
Make sure the patient has adequate renal perfusion

437
00:21:59.250 --> 00:22:01.890
that the blood pressure is reasonable.

438
00:22:01.890 --> 00:22:06.890
Maintain a map of at least 65 millimeters of mercury.

439
00:22:06.960 --> 00:22:10.350
The board may ask you how to calculate a map.

440
00:22:10.350 --> 00:22:14.430
Remember systolic plus two times a diastolic pressure

441
00:22:14.430 --> 00:22:15.780
divided by three.

442
00:22:15.780 --> 00:22:17.073
They may ask you that.

443
00:22:18.150 --> 00:22:22.920
Avoid exposure to aggravating factors in patients with AKI.

444
00:22:22.920 --> 00:22:25.410
So don't give them contrast studies,

445
00:22:25.410 --> 00:22:27.420
don't give them toxic meds,

446
00:22:27.420 --> 00:22:31.473
hold your ACE and ARBs until the renal function improves.

447
00:22:32.340 --> 00:22:34.830
It's true nonoliguric patients do better

448
00:22:34.830 --> 00:22:37.470
than those with lower urine outputs,

449
00:22:37.470 --> 00:22:39.870
but don't give them diuretics to make 'em pee

450
00:22:39.870 --> 00:22:41.200
because it doesn't improve

451
00:22:41.200 --> 00:22:44.460
the renal function, it increases mortality,

452
00:22:44.460 --> 00:22:46.650
unless they're volume overloaded.

453
00:22:46.650 --> 00:22:49.487
And in that case, yes, you're gonna give them diuretics.

454
00:22:49.487 --> 00:22:51.930
Typically, IV Lasix,

455
00:22:51.930 --> 00:22:54.300
you may want to use a Lasix drip.

456
00:22:54.300 --> 00:22:56.670
If you're not able to do it with boluses,

457
00:22:56.670 --> 00:22:58.740
you can substitute Bumex

458
00:22:58.740 --> 00:23:00.873
and dialysis as a last resort.

459
00:23:01.950 --> 00:23:03.570
What about hyperkalemia?

460
00:23:03.570 --> 00:23:05.896
You see that in AKI as well.

461
00:23:05.896 --> 00:23:08.220
We usually give calcium gluconate

462
00:23:08.220 --> 00:23:11.550
to stabilize and protect our membranes

463
00:23:11.550 --> 00:23:13.320
and avoid arrhythmias.

464
00:23:13.320 --> 00:23:15.000
It's temporary.

465
00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:19.200
We also use things to shift potassium intracellularly.

466
00:23:19.200 --> 00:23:20.910
Again, this is temporary,

467
00:23:20.910 --> 00:23:24.360
insulin glucose, albuterol inhalation,

468
00:23:24.360 --> 00:23:26.100
sodium bicarb drips,

469
00:23:26.100 --> 00:23:29.370
it buys us some time to get rid of the potassium

470
00:23:29.370 --> 00:23:31.050
from the system.

471
00:23:31.050 --> 00:23:34.295
For many years, we used something called Kayexalate.

472
00:23:34.295 --> 00:23:35.460
Give it orally.

473
00:23:35.460 --> 00:23:37.290
We use sorbitol with it to keep it

474
00:23:37.290 --> 00:23:39.900
from concreting in the bowel until we learn

475
00:23:39.900 --> 00:23:42.750
that it may cause colonic necrosis.

476
00:23:42.750 --> 00:23:45.240
So we're not using that very much anymore.

477
00:23:45.240 --> 00:23:47.910
There's also no good data that it works

478
00:23:47.910 --> 00:23:50.728
despite using it for a century or more.

479
00:23:50.728 --> 00:23:52.770
We now have two other ail genes.

480
00:23:52.770 --> 00:23:55.080
We have patiromer or Veltassa,

481
00:23:55.080 --> 00:23:57.960
and sodium zirconium or Lokelma.

482
00:23:57.960 --> 00:24:00.480
Both of these are slow-acting,

483
00:24:00.480 --> 00:24:02.523
and they tend to be expensive.

484
00:24:03.635 --> 00:24:06.810
And patients with acidosis, we give them bicarb

485
00:24:06.810 --> 00:24:09.950
if the serum bicarb is less than 15

486
00:24:09.950 --> 00:24:12.200
or the pH less than 7.2.

487
00:24:16.650 --> 00:24:17.880
In patient AKI,

488
00:24:17.880 --> 00:24:20.340
urgent dialysis is not indicated

489
00:24:20.340 --> 00:24:23.040
in which of the following situations.

490
00:24:23.040 --> 00:24:26.130
Hyperkalemia refractory to medical therapy,

491
00:24:26.130 --> 00:24:29.289
volume overload unresponsive to diuretics,

492
00:24:29.289 --> 00:24:33.300
metabolic acidosis, pH 7.25,

493
00:24:33.300 --> 00:24:34.953
or uremic pericarditis.

494
00:24:40.170 --> 00:24:43.290
And we just told you the answer a couple slides before,

495
00:24:43.290 --> 00:24:44.123
and you're right.

496
00:24:44.123 --> 00:24:48.540
It's metabolic acidosis with a reasonable pH.

497
00:24:48.540 --> 00:24:51.480
So who gets dialysis in AKI?

498
00:24:51.480 --> 00:24:56.480
Metabolic acidosis, pH less than 7.1 or bicarb doesn't work.

499
00:24:57.420 --> 00:25:00.960
Uremic encephalopathies, pericarditis,

500
00:25:00.960 --> 00:25:04.080
those folks need dialysis.

501
00:25:04.080 --> 00:25:06.900
Fluid overload refractory to diuretics,

502
00:25:06.900 --> 00:25:09.900
severe hyperkalemia refractory to therapy,

503
00:25:09.900 --> 00:25:12.303
certain poisonings and intoxications.

504
00:25:13.140 --> 00:25:17.520
Remember to prevent AKI maintain a good blood pressure,

505
00:25:17.520 --> 00:25:19.470
use pressors if needed.

506
00:25:19.470 --> 00:25:21.030
And your cirrhotic patients,

507
00:25:21.030 --> 00:25:22.725
if you're gonna do a paracentesis,

508
00:25:22.725 --> 00:25:26.032
make sure you give them albumin infusions.

509
00:25:26.032 --> 00:25:28.170
Your chemotherapy patients,

510
00:25:28.170 --> 00:25:32.640
make sure you hydrate 'em and use allopurinol before chemo.

511
00:25:32.640 --> 00:25:35.190
Don't give 'em nephrotoxic meds.

512
00:25:35.190 --> 00:25:38.936
Don't use contrast in patients who are at risk.

513
00:25:38.936 --> 00:25:42.510
Patients of rhabdo, give them lots of fluids.

514
00:25:42.510 --> 00:25:44.043
Pre-op surgical patients.

515
00:25:44.043 --> 00:25:46.740
make sure they have adequate volume going in

516
00:25:46.740 --> 00:25:49.140
and consider holding an ACE or an ARB

517
00:25:49.140 --> 00:25:51.063
if their blood pressure is borderline.

518
00:25:52.020 --> 00:25:55.830
Patient AKI are more likely to get CKD later

519
00:25:55.830 --> 00:25:57.480
as well as premature death.

520
00:25:57.480 --> 00:26:00.120
So we wanted to do a good job in caring for them

521
00:26:00.120 --> 00:26:01.323
with their condition.

522
00:26:02.310 --> 00:26:04.560
Now, the kidney and the heart,

523
00:26:04.560 --> 00:26:08.193
our bosom buddies have been so for many, many years.

524
00:26:09.180 --> 00:26:12.936
Disease in one tends to cause disease in the other.

525
00:26:12.936 --> 00:26:17.340
Cardiovascular disease responsible for 50% of deaths

526
00:26:17.340 --> 00:26:19.738
in patients with renal failure,

527
00:26:19.738 --> 00:26:22.121
and the government has recognized this

528
00:26:22.121 --> 00:26:25.233
and developed for us the cardiorenal syndrome.

529
00:26:26.160 --> 00:26:29.585
Type 1 is where acute heart failure causes AKI.

530
00:26:29.585 --> 00:26:34.215
Type 2 with chronic heart failure causes CKD.

531
00:26:34.215 --> 00:26:38.059
Type 3 AKI causes heart failure.

532
00:26:38.059 --> 00:26:43.059
Type 4 is CKD develops chronic heart failure.

533
00:26:44.010 --> 00:26:48.090
And Type 5 is when acute systemic disorders

534
00:26:48.090 --> 00:26:50.940
cause both the kidneys and the heart to dysfunction

535
00:26:50.940 --> 00:26:53.880
at the same time like sepsis for example.

536
00:26:53.880 --> 00:26:56.910
The board will not ask you Type 1 versus Type 2

537
00:26:56.910 --> 00:26:59.040
to Type 3 but to know there is something

538
00:26:59.040 --> 00:27:02.433
called a cardiorenal syndrome and why that there is.

539
00:27:04.020 --> 00:27:05.100
Your last question.

540
00:27:05.100 --> 00:27:07.740
So which one of the following is true?

541
00:27:07.740 --> 00:27:10.230
ACE inhibitors enhanced angiotensin 2

542
00:27:10.230 --> 00:27:12.450
mediated vasoconstriction,

543
00:27:12.450 --> 00:27:15.960
angiotensin 2 inhibits secretion of aldosterone

544
00:27:15.960 --> 00:27:17.790
and vasopressin,

545
00:27:17.790 --> 00:27:20.460
ACE inhibitor therapy should be stopped

546
00:27:20.460 --> 00:27:23.665
if there's a 10 to 15% increase in creatinine,

547
00:27:23.665 --> 00:27:27.243
and ACE inhibitors dilate efferent arterioles.

548
00:27:33.150 --> 00:27:36.330
And your vote is for the last one.

549
00:27:36.330 --> 00:27:37.200
Excellent.

550
00:27:37.200 --> 00:27:40.440
ACE inhibitors dilate efferent arterioles.

551
00:27:40.440 --> 00:27:43.710
Here's a nice picture with the angiotensin renin system,

552
00:27:43.710 --> 00:27:45.063
sitting there on the right.

553
00:27:46.560 --> 00:27:49.530
Renin is a hormone released by the kidneys.

554
00:27:49.530 --> 00:27:54.230
It helps to convert angiotensinogen in the angiotensin 1.

555
00:27:56.340 --> 00:28:00.060
Angiotensin 2 is formed from angiotensin 1

556
00:28:00.060 --> 00:28:04.050
using the ACE enzyme.

557
00:28:04.050 --> 00:28:06.780
Angiotensin 2 is the bad guy.

558
00:28:06.780 --> 00:28:10.710
It causes vasoconstriction, sodium retention,

559
00:28:10.710 --> 00:28:13.320
fluid retention due to vasopressin release.

560
00:28:13.320 --> 00:28:17.370
All this stuff causes heart failure and dysrhythmias.

561
00:28:17.370 --> 00:28:20.250
So we wanna block that conversion of angiotensin 1

562
00:28:20.250 --> 00:28:22.050
to angiotensin 2.

563
00:28:22.050 --> 00:28:25.200
We use ACE inhibitors and ARBs to do so.

564
00:28:25.200 --> 00:28:26.656
When you block that,

565
00:28:26.656 --> 00:28:31.350
the precursors build up so you get higher levels of renin,

566
00:28:31.350 --> 00:28:33.600
angiotensin 1, and bradykinin,

567
00:28:33.600 --> 00:28:37.538
which causes the cough that you see with ACE inhibitors.

568
00:28:37.538 --> 00:28:39.599
But ACE inhibitors do good things,

569
00:28:39.599 --> 00:28:41.580
they cause a central enhancement

570
00:28:41.580 --> 00:28:43.650
of parasympathetic activity.

571
00:28:43.650 --> 00:28:46.170
So they break that cycle of dysrhythmias

572
00:28:46.170 --> 00:28:49.200
causes you not to retain fluid,

573
00:28:49.200 --> 00:28:51.450
so it helps with heart failure as well.

574
00:28:51.450 --> 00:28:54.843
So decreases sudden death and helps with heart failure.

575
00:28:56.070 --> 00:29:00.240
Now, the ACE inhibitors do dilate the efferent arteriole.

576
00:29:00.240 --> 00:29:04.140
What that does is increase the flow through the glomerulus

577
00:29:04.140 --> 00:29:07.620
but also decreases the pressure in the glomerulus,

578
00:29:07.620 --> 00:29:10.170
and the excretion of creatinine is a pressure

579
00:29:10.170 --> 00:29:11.760
and not a volume effect.

580
00:29:11.760 --> 00:29:13.770
So creatinines tend to go up

581
00:29:13.770 --> 00:29:16.020
when you put a patient on an ACE inhibitor,

582
00:29:16.020 --> 00:29:18.250
and that's okay as long as it doesn't go up

583
00:29:18.250 --> 00:29:21.085
to 20 to 30% over the baseline.

584
00:29:21.085 --> 00:29:22.650
That's not good.

585
00:29:22.650 --> 00:29:23.940
That means there may be something

586
00:29:23.940 --> 00:29:25.752
like renal artery stenosis.

587
00:29:25.752 --> 00:29:28.590
And those patients, you might want to hold

588
00:29:28.590 --> 00:29:32.910
that ACE or ARB until you figure out what's going on.

589
00:29:32.910 --> 00:29:34.020
Again, you wanna rule out

590
00:29:34.020 --> 00:29:36.855
bilateral renal-artery obstruction.

591
00:29:36.855 --> 00:29:41.040
You wanna rule out a intravascular volume depletion

592
00:29:41.040 --> 00:29:43.350
and the use of other nephrotoxic meds

593
00:29:43.350 --> 00:29:47.820
as a cause for that before restarting your ACE or your ARB.

594
00:29:47.820 --> 00:29:49.290
So here are your answers.

595
00:29:49.290 --> 00:29:52.020
This group actually did quite well on these questions

596
00:29:52.020 --> 00:29:53.880
compared to groups in the past.

597
00:29:53.880 --> 00:29:56.040
So looking forward to doing well

598
00:29:56.040 --> 00:29:59.015
when we hit chronic kidney disease later.

599
00:29:59.015 --> 00:30:01.598
(bright music)

